
[1]sunder

   SUN'DER, v.t.

   1. To part; to separate; to divide; to disunite in almost any manner,
   either by rending, cutting, or breaking; as, to sunder a rope or cord;
   to sunder a limb or joint; to sunder friends, or the ties of
   friendship. The executioner sunders the head from the body at a stroke.
   A mountain may be sundered by an earthquake.

   Bring me lightning, give me thunder;

   --Jove may kill, but ne'er shall sunder.

   2. To expose to the sun. [Provincial in England.]

                       SUN'DER, n. In sunder, in tow.

   He cutteth the spear in sunder. Ps.46.
